# Bug Fixes & Enterprise Migration Implementation Plan

This plan addresses all 9 bugs previously fixed and newly outlines the Enterprise Database Migration (Phase 2), moving from hardcoded documents to dynamic categories and version-controlled letters.

## Enterprise Migration Proposed Changes

### Database Models (Sequelize)
#### [NEW] server/src/models/document_category.model.js
- Stores document types, separating `identity`, `family`, `education`, and `employee_letters`. Has `is_required` flag.

#### [NEW] server/src/models/document_version.model.js
- Stores individual PDF/Image versions for Employee Letters. 

#### [MODIFY] server/src/models/document.model.js
- Link `category_id` rather than hardcoding category text.

#### [MODIFY] server/src/models/index.js
- Establish the new `Category hasMany Documents`, `Document hasMany Versions`, etc.

### Core Logic & Services
#### [NEW] server/src/services/document.service.js
- Consolidate business logic for calculating the 15-required-document completion percentage.

#### [NEW] server/src/middlewares/upload.middleware.js
- Robust Multer setup that specifically isolates storage into `storage/e-dossier/EMP_ID/category`.

### Controllers & Routes
#### [NEW] server/src/controllers/letter.controller.js
- Endpoints `POST /api/letters/version` and get versions.

#### [MODIFY] server/src/controllers/report.controller.js
- Deprecate old counting logic in favor of using `document.service.js` which relies on `is_required` flags.

#### [MODIFY] server/src/seed.js
- Adjust the seeder to populate the new `document_categories` table before assigning random incomplete docs to employees.

---

## Verification Plan
### Automated Tests
- Drop database schema and re-run the updated `node server/src/seed.js`.
- Start server `npm run dev:server`.

### Manual Verification
- Use `browser_subagent` to upload a new document to verify Multer creates the `EMP001` subfolder.
- Upload two versions of the exact same Employee Letter to verify the `document_versions` table works.
- Confirm dashboard percentage exactly matches the `15-document` rule (excluding optional SKs).
